               <label>MSA name (trans.)</label>
               <name xml:lang="ara-x-DMG">Arwād</name>
               <label>Local name (trans.)</label>
               <name xml:lang="ara-Latn" type="latLoc">Arwēd</name>
            </head>
            <div type="positioning">
               <head>Geo location</head>
               <p>
                  <geo>34°51'N 35°51'E</geo>
                  <country>Syria</country>
               </p>
            </div>
            <div type="typology">
               <head>Typology (Local)</head>
               <p rend="typology">East (Mashreq) › Levant › Syria › Coast</p>
               <p>Sedentary dialect with characteristic features distinguishing it from mainland varieties</p>
            </div>
            <div type="general">
               <p>Arwad is Syria’s only inhabited island. It is situated three kilometres off the coast
                  opposite the port town of Tartous. Its population is about 2,000. The island is one of the last places in the
                  Eastern Mediterranean where traditional wooden ships are built.</p>
            </div>
            <div type="researchHistory">
               <p>The Linguistic Atlas of Syria (<rs type="bibl" ref="zotid:Y5WWYMLB">Behnstedt (1997)</rs>) contains
                  some important data on Arwad (no. 256 on the maps). <rs type="bibl" ref="zotid:UQFLSCBA">Solaÿmân and Charles (1972)</rs> is
                  a detailed lexical study on sailing and maritime life. <rs type="bibl" ref="zotid:XJFHMUQM">Procházka (2013)</rs> includes
                  a short grammatical sketch and two texts on boat-building, with English translation.</p>
            </div>

            <div>
                 <p>To view publications on this variety click <rs type="bibl" ref="bibl:geo:Arwad">here</rs>.</p>
            </div>

